1. CLI Execution (Command Line)
For a CLI, you want to trigger your agent manually by typing a command in your terminal. This is ideal for testing logic or running batch updates on issues.

Implementation Strategy:
Create a cli.js file that acts as your entry point, allowing you to pass arguments like the issue number.

JavaScript
// cli.js
import { processPrompt } from './src/ai.js';
import { addComment } from './src/github.js';

const [,, owner, repo, issueNumber, prompt] = process.argv;

async function run() {
  console.log("Analyzing...");
  const aiResponse = await processPrompt(prompt);
  await addComment(owner, repo, issueNumber, aiResponse);
  console.log("Comment posted successfully!");
}

run();
How to run it:

Bash
node cli.js my-username my-repo 123 "Please summarize this issue."
2. Web UI Execution
If you want a graphical interface to interact with the bot, you have two primary paths:

A. The "Quick & Professional" Path (Streamlit or Gradio)
If you know a little Python, you can use Gradio or Streamlit. Even though your core logic is in Node.js, you can wrap the Node script in a Python subprocess call or rewrite the logic in Python to create a dashboard in minutes.

Example (Gradio):

Python
import gradio as gr
import subprocess

def trigger_agent(repo, issue, prompt):
    # Calls your Node.js script
    result = subprocess.run(['node', 'cli.js', 'user', repo, issue, prompt], capture_output=True)
    return result.stdout.decode()

demo = gr.Interface(fn=trigger_agent, inputs=["text", "text", "text"], outputs="text")
demo.launch()
B. The "Full Stack" Path (Fastify/Express + Frontend)
If you want to keep everything in JavaScript, build a simple web dashboard using Fastify or Express with a frontend (React or HTML/Tailwind).

Backend Route: Create an endpoint like POST /api/run-agent.

Frontend: Build a simple form with fields for "Repo," "Issue #," and "Task Description."

Action: The frontend sends a fetch request to your backend, which then executes your src/github.js and src/ai.js logic.
